# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: claire-m-fraser
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp was born in Catonsville, Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp grew up in Catonsville, approximately 20 miles from the University of Maryland, College Park campus where she would work for nearly four decades.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Timothy's School and Western High School.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Between 1913 and 1915, Stamp taught physical education at Catonsville High School.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] During the summers of 1914 and 1915, she enrolled in a "College Courses for Teachers" program at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp then enrolled at Sophie Newcomb College (the women's school associated with Tulane University).
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] She spent the summers of 1915 and 1916 teaching physical education at Alfred University (in western New York State), and she returned to Maryland in the summer of 1917 to serve as summer school instructor at the University of Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] As World War I approached, Stamp applied her experience as a recreation director and classwork in sociology as a social worker for the War Work Council of the Young Women's Christian Association (YWCA), where she formed recreation programs for female factory workers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] She led recreation education for the 5,000 women employed at the Old Hickory Munitions Plant (external link) in Jacksonville, Tennessee 1918–1919.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] During 1919 and 1920 Stamp served as the director of recreation for female workers at the Industrial Service Center of the YWCA in New Orleans while finishing her studies at Newcomb College.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1921, Stamp graduated from with a degree in sociology.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] After graduation, Stamp accepted a position with the Red Cross as a field representative in the South.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Soon after, University of Maryland president Albert F.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Woods offered her the position of Dean of Women, which she accepted.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] Stamp served as Dean of Women at the University of Maryland, College Park for 38 years.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] She initially took the position as a one-year contract, which was renewed for a second year before being extended to comprise the remainder of her career.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] The university had just begun admitting women in 1916.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] During Stamp's tenure as Dean of Women, enrollment of female students increased from 93 in 1922 to approximately 4,000 in 1960.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1923, she organized the Maryland State Association of Deans of Women, which soon gained membership from neighboring Delaware, Virginia, and Washington, DC.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] In 1924, Stamp earned a master's degree in sociology at the University of Maryland, where she completed a thesis entitled "Community Organization in Maryland Welfare Organization." She undertook additional graduate work at Catholic University of America and American University.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] When Stamp retired in December 1960, the University of Maryland Board of Regents awarded Stamp the title *dean of women emeritus*.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] *Emeritus* is the highest faculty honor bestowed by the board, and Stamp the first to receive the title.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adele-hagner-stamp] The Baltimore Sun, reporting on her retirement, mused that her 38 years of service was likely the "longest record of continuous service at a single school of any dean of women in the United States" (page 11).
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Born and raised in Baltimore County, Jones graduated from the University of Maryland, Baltimore County before working in Baltimore County government until 2014.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Following the death of state delegate Joan N.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Parker, she was appointed to the Maryland House of Delegates in 1997, and was subsequently elected to her first four-year term in 1998.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She was named speaker pro tempore by House Speaker Michael E.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Busch in 2003, serving in this position until her election as Speaker following Busch's death in 2019.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During her speakership, Jones supported the implementation of the Blueprint for Maryland's Future as well as efforts to enshrine abortion rights into the Constitution of Maryland and ensure equity in Maryland's newly-created recreational cannabis and sports betting industries.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She stepped down as speaker in December 2025, and withdrew from her re-election bid in February 2026.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Born in the historically African-American community of Cowdensville in Arbutus, Maryland, Jones was the second of five children.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She attended Baltimore County public schools and graduated from Lansdowne High School, and later attended the University of Maryland, Baltimore County, where she earned a B.A. degree in psychology in 1976.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] After graduating, Jones worked as a clerk in the Baltimore County's Office of Central Services.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She first became involved in politics in 1979, when started working as a legislative officer for Baltimore County Executive Donald P.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 1987, Jones became a member of Woman Power, Inc., a voter education organization.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] From 1989 to 1995, she worked as the director of the Office of Minority Affairs in Baltimore County, Maryland, afterwards working as the executive director of the Office of Fair Practices and Community Affairs until 2011.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones later worked as the deputy director of the Office of Human Resources until 2014.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also founded the Baltimore County African American Cultural Festival.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones was a member of the Baltimore County Democratic Central Committee and applied to fill a vacancy in the Maryland House of Delegates following the death of then-state delegate Joan N.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Her candidacy was backed by several local area politicians, including Baltimore County Executive Dutch Ruppersberger, state senators Delores G.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Kelley and Shirley Nathan-Pulliam, and state delegate Emmett C.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The Baltimore County Democratic Central Committee voted to nominate her out of a field of 16 candidates.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Her nomination was confirmed by Governor Parris Glendening, and she was sworn in on October 21, 1997.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones was a member of the Appropriations Committee from 1997 to 2003, afterwards serving on the Ways and Means Committee for part of the 2003 legislative session before rejoining the Appropriations Committee, where she remained until her election as Speaker in 2019.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She returned to the Appropriations Committee in 2026, after stepping down as speaker.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also served as the chair of the Capital Budget Subcommittee from 2003 to 2019, which allowed her to get to know delegates from across the state and the projects they wanted built in their districts.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] From 2003 to 2019, Jones served as the speaker pro tempore of the Maryland House of Delegates, the first African-American woman to serve in this position.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In this capacity, she filled in for House Speaker Michael E.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Busch when he was absent and worked to quash personal issues with delegates before they became problems.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In December 2008, following an unexpected drop in state revenues, Governor Martin O'Malley ordered a furlough for state employees.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones voluntarily participated in the state employee furlough later that month.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The constitutionality of doing this was unclear, as the Constitution of Maryland prohibits the state government from furloughing state legislators.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2020, Jones was named co-chair of the Maryland Women for Biden group, alongside Prince George's County Executive Angela Alsobrooks, State Senate President Pro Tem Melony G.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Griffith, and Maryland Democratic Party Chair Yvette Lewis.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In January 2021, she condemned the January 6 United States Capitol attack, calling it "nothing less than sedition".
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones was an at-large delegate to the 2024 Democratic National Convention, pledged to Kamala Harris.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones missed most of the 2026 legislative session, having only attended a handful of days during the 90 day session.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] A spokesperson for House Speaker Joseline Peña-Melnyk told *Maryland Matters* that Jones was out with an undisclosed medical condition and it was not known if or when she might return.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In February 2026, Jones withdrew as a candidate in the 2026 election.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones took over as Acting Speaker of the Maryland House of Delegates on April 7, 2019, following the death of then-Speaker Michael E.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] A few days later, following Busch's funeral, she announced that she would run for Speaker, becoming the first candidate to declare an intention to run.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She withdrew her candidacy later that month after failing to secure enough support, and endorsed state delegate Dereck E.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones is both the first female and first African-American speaker in Maryland state history, and only the third Black woman to serve as state House speaker overall following Karen Bass of California and Sheila Oliver of New Jersey.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In September 2019, she selected state delegate Sheree Sample-Hughes to succeed her as speaker pro tempore.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also supported efforts to enshrine the right to an abortion into the Constitution of Maryland, an effort previously shepherded by her predecessor.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In April 2022, Jones signed 103 Maryland measures into law together with Republican Governor Larry Hogan and Maryland Senate president pro tempore Melony G.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Griffith, marking the first time that two Black women had taken part in such a ceremony as Maryland's presiding officers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] On December 4, 2025, Jones announced that she would step down as speaker of the Maryland House of Delegates, effective immediately.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2019, after the Alabama General Assembly passed the Human Life Protection Act, Jones said she would continue Busch's efforts to codify abortion rights in the Constitution of Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2022 legislative session, she introduced legislation that would create a ballot referendum on codifying the right to abortion access into the state constitution.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed the House of Delegates, but died in the Maryland Senate after Senate President Bill Ferguson declined to put the bill up for a vote.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Jones promised to reintroduce the abortion referendum bill during the 2023 legislative session, during which it passed and was signed into law by Governor Wes Moore.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] On March 12, 2020, a week after Governor Larry Hogan declared a state of emergency for the COVID-19 pandemic in Maryland, Jones told legislators to prioritize work on "the most critical bills" in case they needed to end the legislative session early for the pandemic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Three days later, she announced that the Maryland General Assembly would adjourn sine die on March 18, but would reconvene for a special legislative session in May, which never happened.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The early adjournment marked the first time the Maryland General Assembly had ended its legislative session early since the American Civil War.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She confirmed the first case of COVID-19 in the Maryland General Assembly on March 22.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Ahead of the legislature's adjournment, Jones introduced legislation to extend temporary unemployment benefits for workers affected by the pandemic, which passed and was signed into law by Governor Larry Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] On March 19, she convened the COVID-19 Response Legislative Workgroup to monitor the state's response to the pandemic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones criticized the lack of transparency from the Hogan administration during the pandemic, especially from the Maryland Department of Health, saying that the administration ignored coronavirus-related health questions as the governor began lifting pandemic-related restrictions.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2020, she questioned the Hogan administration's decision to begin reopening the state, requesting data to justify the decision.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She later appeared in an ad to encourage voters to promote voting by mail in the 2020 Maryland's 7th congressional district special election.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2020, Jones wrote to the Maryland State Board of Elections to increase the state's voting centers and mail-in ballot drop-off locations in Montgomery County and Baltimore.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2020, after Governor Hogan announced plans to hold a full in-person election for the 2020 general election, Jones encouraged voters to register for a mail-in ballot online and sent a letter to Hogan demanding that he provide voters with prepaid postage for ballot applications.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2020, Jones co-signed a letter to congressional leaders requesting "additional, flexible funding" for state and local governments amid budget deficiencies in response to the pandemic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In June 2020, she informed state Budget Secretary David R.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Brinkley that the legislature would cut $4.8 million, or about five percent of its annual budget, from its 2020 budget.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In August 2020, Jones called on Hogan to allocate funding toward lawyers to help tenants at risk of being evicted during the pandemic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones declined to hold a special legislative session to pass legislation to address housing and policing issues amid the pandemic, saying that these issues would be dealt with during the 2021 legislative session.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In November 2020, she issued restrictions on meetings in the House of Delegates ahead of the 2021 legislative session, including capacity restrictions on legislator offices and a ban on meetings with lobbyists.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2021 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation to reform the state's unemployment insurance program, which passed and signed into law by Governor Hogan, and another that would extend the state's earned income tax credit to Individual Taxpayer Identification Number taxpayers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2021, she called for the resignation of state Labor Secretary Tiffany Robinson, citing her slow adoption of the unemployment reforms and poor communications with claimants.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2021, Jones announced that the Maryland State House would reopen to visitors and tourists.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In August 2021, Jones urged Hogan to extend the state's emergency declaration amid a rise in cases from the delta variant.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She later expressed support of a Maryland State Board of Education policy mandating universal masking in public schools and called on Hogan to implement the policy immediately.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2004 legislative session, Jones introduced a bill to cap tuition increases at state universities to five percent a year, but only if the state increased its spending on higher education by five percent a year over the next three years.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed, but was vetoed by Governor Bob Ehrlich.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2016 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation to give lawmakers oversight over Governor Larry Hogan's appointments to the Baltimore County Board of Education.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill failed to pass out of the Baltimore County Delegation.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also supported a bill that removed the state's ability to spend tax money on portable air conditioners in schools, and the College Affordability Act, which would match contributions made by low-income families toward college savings accounts.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2018 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation to strip the Maryland Board of Public Works of its oversight and management of the state's annual "beg-a-thon", in which school system leaders appear before the board to request additional school construction funding.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed and was vetoed by Governor Larry Hogan, which was later overridden by the Maryland General Assembly.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In October 2019, Jones sent a letter to Governor Hogan urging him to accept the amount recommended by an attorney representing the state's historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) in a 13-year-old lawsuit against the state over funding disparities.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2020 legislative session, she introduced and testified in support of legislation that would force the state to settle the lawsuit by annually distributing $57.7 million to the state's HBCUs over a decade.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed, but was vetoed by Governor Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill was reintroduced during the 2021 legislative session, during which it unanimously passed and was signed into law by Governor Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2019 legislative session, Jones supported legislation to increase state education spending by $850 million as part of the implementation of the Blueprint for Maryland's Future.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill became law without Governor Hogan's signature.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2019, Jones said she would support legislation to fully implement the Blueprint and to fund new school construction.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2020 legislative session, she introduced the Built to Learn Act, which would allow the Maryland Stadium Authority to issue up to $2.2 billion in bonds to pay for school construction projects, and the Blueprint implementation bill.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Both bills passed, but Hogan vetoed the Blueprint bill while signing the Built to Learn Act into law, which was amended to become dependent on the Blueprint bill passing to go into effect.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The Maryland General Assembly overrode Hogan's veto of the Blueprint for Maryland's Future during the 2021 legislative session.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones, to account for the impact Hogan's veto would have on the Blueprint's implementation, introduced a bill to adjust the bill's implementation timeline, which passed and became law without Hogan's signature.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2023 legislative session, Jones introduced the SERVE Act, which created a "service year option" in schools that would pay high school graduates $15 per hour for at least 30 hours a week for work in service to the community.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed and was signed into law by Governor Wes Moore.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In August 2021, Jones said she supported the construction of a wind farm off the shore of Ocean City, Maryland, calling it "one of the state's most impactful and innovative renewable energy projects".
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2013, Jones voted in favor of the Firearm Safety Act of 2013, a bill that placed restrictions on firearm purchases and magazine capacity in semi-automatic rifles.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In November 2023, she expressed disappointment with a Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals ruling that struck down a provision of the Firearm Safety Act that required handgun owners to obtain a "handgun qualification license" to buy a handgun.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2020 legislative session, Jones spoke in support of a bill to restrict the transfer of rifles or shotguns to people prohibited from owning handguns.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed, but was vetoed by Governor Larry Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2022 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation that would require gun shops to have increased safety measures, including 24-hour burglary alarm systems and anti-vehicle barriers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bills passed, but were vetoed by Governor Hogan; the legislature overrode his veto the following day.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2013, Jones voted in favor of legislation to repeal the death penalty in Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2020, following the murder of George Floyd, Jones announced the formation of a bipartisan work group to review police reform and accountability in the state.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In June 2020, she wrote a letter to Governor Larry Hogan calling on him to enact executive orders to immediately reform the state's police use of force policies.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The work group released its recommendations in October, which included repealing the state's Law Enforcement Officers' Bill of Rights and regulating the types of force that police could use during arrests.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2021 legislative session, Jones introduced the Police Reform and Accountability Act, which implemented the work group's recommendations.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] It was passed and vetoed by Governor Larry Hogan; the Maryland General Assembly voted to override Hogan's veto the following day.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2014 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation to create diversion programs for first-time marijuana offenders.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2021, Jones said she supported a ballot referendum to legalize recreational marijuana in Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2022 legislative session, she introduced legislation creating the referendum, which passed and was overwhelmingly approved by voters in the 2022 general election.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In June 2019, Jones expressed disappointment with the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Lamone*, saying that she hoped the court would offer a "national solution to what is clearly a national problem".
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2021 legislative session, Jones supported legislation that would require elections for county commissioners to only be decided by voters within the districts in which the candidate is running, calling it a "historic civil rights legislation".
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2021, Jones announced the formation of the Legislative Redistricting Advisory Commission, which was tasked with coming up with new congressional and legislative maps to pass during the 2020 redistricting cycle.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The LRAC proposed four draft maps for the state's new congressional districts in November, two of which would have likely strengthened Democrats' chances of defeating Representative Andy Harris, the state's lone congressional Republican, in Maryland's 1st congressional district.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Democratic leaders of the Maryland General Assembly voted to consider the first of these two maps, which passed, but was vetoed by Governor Larry Hogan; the Maryland General Assembly voted to override Hogan's veto the same day.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The maps were struck down by Judge Lynne A.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Battaglia, who ruled that the maps were "a product of extreme partisan gerrymandering", a ruling that Jones expressed disappointment with.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones introduced replacement maps shortly after the ruling, which proposed a map that undid changes to the 1st district.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The new redistricting plan passed and was signed into law by Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2005, Jones was one of 36 Democratic state delegates to vote against a bill to legalize slot machines in Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2012 legislative session, Jones introduced legislation to limit retirement bonuses for select county workers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2012, Jones voted in favor of the Civil Marriage Protection Act, which legalized same sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In December 2019, Jones announced the implementation of various physical and logistical changes to the Maryland House of Delegates, including conversion of bathrooms behind the House chamber to include a gender-neutral bathroom.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2019, in one of her first actions as Speaker, Jones called for the removal of a plaque dedicated to Union and Confederate soldiers who fought in the American Civil War.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The State House Trust voted in June 2020 to remove the plaque.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Following its removal, Jones called for the repeal of "Maryland, My Maryland" as the official state anthem.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She supported legislation to repeal the state song during the 2021 legislative session, which was signed into law by Governor Larry Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2020 legislative session, Jones supported legislation to provide $375.5 million toward modernizing Pimlico Race Course and Laurel Park.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] The bill passed and became law without Governor Hogan's signature.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In January 2020, following the sentencing of former state delegate Tawanna P.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Gaines for misusing campaign funds for personal benefit, Jones said she would introduce legislation to ban family members from serving as campaign treasurers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2021 legislative session, Jones unveiled her "Black Agenda", which included a package of bills to increase equity in business and reduce barriers to financial resources.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also introduced legislation to establish the framework for the sports betting industry following Maryland voters approving a ballot referendum to legalize sports betting during the 2020 general election.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] These bills all passed and were signed into law by Governor Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In February 2021, Jones announced that she would require criminal justice bills to include racial impact statements in their legislative analysis.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In August 2022, Jones said she supported bringing the new Federal Bureau of Investigation headquarters to Prince George's County, writing to General Services Administration administrator Robin Carnahan that locating it there would help the federal government meet its equity goals.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2006, Jones voted to override Governor Bob Ehrlich's veto of a bill capping electricity bill rate increases at 15 percent.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In 2013, Jones voted in favor of legislation to index the state's gas taxes to inflation to pay for transportation projects.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In July 2019, Jones proposed cutting the state's tax credits to pay for the Blueprint for Maryland's Future.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2020 legislative session, she ruled out increasing state sales, property, or income taxes to pay for education reforms.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] During the 2022 legislative session, Jones introduced a package of bills to eliminate state taxes on the sales of child care and medical items, and another bill creating a 30-day gas tax holiday following a spike in gas prices as the result of the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] All of these bills passed unanimously and were signed into law by Governor Larry Hogan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] In May 2022, Jones declined to hold a special legislative session to prevent the state's gas tax from increasing 7 cents per gallon to adjust for inflation, and blamed big oil companies for "exploiting global uncertainty" to significantly increase gas prices.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She also declined to extend the state's gas tax holiday, which she said would have "long-term consequences" on the state's infrastructure.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] Jones supported the construction of the Red Line and criticized Governor Larry Hogan's cancellation of the transit project, which she said would have been "an economic engine for the area".
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] After Governor Wes Moore announced the revival of the Red Line in 2023, Jones supported a study to explore extending the transit line to Sparrows Point, Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/adrienne-a-jones] She has two sons and attends religious services at the Union Bethel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Randallstown, Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She was born in Baltimore, Maryland, in 1925, the fifth of 12 children of Phillip Moten Kane and Mary Gough Kane.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Her paternal grandfather, Henry Kane, was born into slavery at Sotterley Plantation in St.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She was active in her community, joining the Eastside Democratic Organization, founding a neighborhood club called "Clean Up for a Better Neighborhood," and organizing educational field trips for local schoolchildren.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] At age 44 she resumed her education, earning a master's degree in social sciences at Morgan State University.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 1973 she received a Fulbright-Hays Scholarship and studied at the University of Ghana at Legon.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Callum became interested in her family history while still an undergraduate, when she wrote a paper titled "The Acquisition of Land by Free Blacks in St.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Mary's County Maryland" for a Black History class.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 1979 she published her first book, *Kane-Butler Genealogy: History of a Black Family*.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She went on to publish many volumes of research documenting the connections between the enslaved and slave holders in Maryland, and U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She also contributed many articles to the *Catholic Review* about the role of people of African descent, such as Mathias de Sousa, in colonial Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 1982 she gave a presentation titled *The Genealogy of a Slave Family of St.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Mary's County, Maryland 1793–1900* at the annual conference of the Association for the Study of African American Life and History (ASALH).
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] That same year, she founded a black genealogical journal, *Flower of the Forest*, named for a tract of land in St.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Mary's County, Maryland, that had been owned by the Butler family for 125 years.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Callum edited and published the journal for 25 years.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She was still publishing online as late as 2014.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Callum's research has helped many people trace their ancestors who were enslaved in Maryland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Francis Xavier Church in East Baltimore, the first Catholic parish officially established for African Americans.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Her research into slave life at the Sotterley Plantation provided the basis for the educational program "Slavery to Freedom," at Sotterley.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Her husband, Solomon Melvin Callum, died in 1975.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She had five children, two of whom predeceased her.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She died in Baltimore on July 22, 2015, of complications from Parkinson's disease.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 2006, a complete set of her published works was donated to the Reginald F.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture in Baltimore.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 2007, the Baltimore chapter of the Afro-American Historical and Genealogical Society was renamed the Agnes Kane Callum chapter in her honor.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] She received an honorary degree in history from St.
[src:claire-m-fraser/agnes-kane-callum] In 2017, the Slave Cabin Exhibition at Sotterley Plantation was dedicated to her memory.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:claire-m-fraser/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:claire-m-fraser/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser was born on November 5, 1955, in Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser was raised by a high school principal and an elementary school teacher in Saugus, MA a suburb of Boston, MA.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] She performed well at school and was always interested in learning.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] She became interested in science after being taught biology in high school.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] At Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (RPI), during her senior year, she performed independent research in a research lab.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser has authored more than 300 publications with more than 50,000 citations, edited four books, and served on the editorial boards of nine scientific journals.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] From 1998 to 2007, Fraser was president and director of The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) in Rockville, MD, and led the teams that sequenced the genomes of bacterial and parasitic pathogens and the first model plant, *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] In 1995, Fraser was part of the team to first sequence the complete genome of a free-living organism—*Haemophilus influenzae*—the bacterium that causes lower respiratory tract infections and meningitis in infants and young children.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] In 2007, Fraser joined the University of Maryland School of Medicine as director of the new Institute for Genome Sciences.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser's work on the 2001 Amerithrax investigation led to the identification of four genetic mutations in the anthrax spores that enabled the FBI to trace the material back to its original source.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] This effort catalyzed the development of the field of microbial forensics.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] She is an expert in microbial forensics and the growing concern about dual uses – research that can provide knowledge and technologies that could be misapplied.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser has led NIAID-funded efforts in the genomics of infectious disease, including the current iteration of the Genome Centers for Infectious Disease.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] These projects both stimulate and enhance ongoing technology development in technology and data cores.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] In 2019, Fraser is serving a one-year term as President-Elect for the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS), which will be followed by a one-year term as AAAS president starting in February 2020 and a one-year term as chair of the Board of Directors in February 2021.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] She notes that "our ability to respond to these challenges has been hampered to a considerable extent by a lack of adequate funding, a tendency to fund 'safer' research projects, and a relative lack of public trust in science.".
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser has been an editor for journals *mBio*, *Journal of Bacteriology*, *Microbial Genomics (journal)*, *Molecular Case Studies*, and *DNA and Cell Biology*.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Since 2006, Fraser has also served as a member of the Board of Directors of Becton, Dickinson and Company (BD), a Fortune 500 medical technology company.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser was previously married to Craig Venter.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Since 2013, she has been married to Jack Kammer, an author who examines gender issues from a male point of view.
[src:claire-m-fraser/claire-m-fraser] Fraser has owned several standard poodles, including Shadow whose genome was sequenced.
